text = "	Now that we know some birds we can start to learn about them. One interesting place to start is by trying to figure out what is [color=papaya_whip]C[/color]’s response to [color=papaya_whip]T[/color]. From what we have learned so far, there doesn't seem to be a rule telling us what this bird is. One way of finding out what bird it is, is by calling out the name of a new bird [color=yellow]x[/color] to it and seeing how it responds. When [color=papaya_whip]C[/color][color=papaya_whip]T[/color] hears [color=yellow]x[/color], it responds by calling out ([color=papaya_whip]CT[/color])[color=yellow]x[/color], which is closer to [color=papaya_whip]C[/color]’s rule, (([color=papaya_whip]C[/color][color=papaya_whip]x[/color])[color=yellow]y[/color])[color=orange]z[/color]=…, but not quite there yet. We can try calling out the name of another bird [color=orange]y[/color]. When we do this, ([color=papaya_whip]CT[/color])[color=yellow]x[/color] responds with (([color=papaya_whip]CT[/color])[color=yellow]x[/color])[color=orange]y[/color]. But now we can apply what we know about [color=papaya_whip]C[/color]: whenever the conversation of the birds looks like (([color=papaya_whip]Cx[/color])[color=yellow]y[/color])[color=orange]z[/color], the result is ([color=papaya_whip]x[/color][color=orange]z[/color])[color=yellow]y[/color]. So (([color=papaya_whip]CT[/color])[color=yellow]x[/color])[color=orange]y[/color] is the same as ([color=papaya_whip]T[/color][color=orange]y[/color])[color=yellow]x[/color]. But now we can apply [color=papaya_whip]T[/color]’s rule: whenever the conversation looks like ([color=papaya_whip]T[/color][color=orange]x[/color])[color=yellow]y[/color], the result is [color=yellow]y[/color][color=orange]x[/color]. Therefore ([color=papaya_whip]T[/color][color=orange]y[/color])[color=yellow]x[/color] is the same as [color=yellow]x[/color][color=orange]y[/color]. So [color=papaya_whip]CT[/color] is a bird [color=papaya_whip]?[/color] with the property that ([color=papaya_whip]?[/color][color=yellow]x[/color])[color=orange]y[/color] = [color=yellow]x[/color][color=orange]y[/color], we happen to know such a bird: [color=papaya_whip]P[/color]. If we call out [color=yellow]x[/color] to [color=papaya_whip]P[/color], [color=papaya_whip]P[/color] will respond with [color=yellow]x[/color]. If we then call out [color=orange]y[/color] to [color=yellow]x[/color] we get [color=yellow]x[/color][color=orange]y[/color] just like in the case for [color=papaya_whip]CT[/color]. So we have figured out that whenever [color=papaya_whip]C[/color] hears [color=papaya_whip]T[/color], it responds with [color=papaya_whip]P[/color].
"
